# Universal Navigation Context & Return Standard

**Owners:** `lib/navigationContext/` · `NavigationReturnBar` · `ProfileReturnBar` (Profile consumer) · capture/restore in `CompanionPageClient.tsx`

**Retires:** Global Return-to-Profile as a separate architecture — Profile is one implementation of this rule.

## Purpose

Whenever a member opens another destination, the platform remembers exact context and provides an easy return. Members explore naturally — they do not get lost.

## Destinations (full return bar + breadcrumbs)

Settings · Experience Controls · Chamber · Boardroom · Evidence Vault · Journal · Projects · Talk It Out · Profile · nested destination workflows

Primary control: `← Back to [Origin]` (contextual — never hard-code per page).

Breadcrumb: every segment clickable (e.g. `Projects › Website Redesign › Task Details`).

## Living Places (minimal)

Welcome Home + subtle leave/return only.

- No persistent breadcrumb trail on glass
- No History clock over the photograph
- Leave **restores originating destination context** when the member entered from a destination — not always Welcome Home

## Stack

`pushFrame` before leave · `popFrame` / `jumpToIndex` on return · `clearStack` on login, sign-up, onboarding, emergency recovery, intentional Welcome Home start-over.

Saving Settings must **not** clear the stack.

## Context restore

scroll · tab · section · accordion · filters · sort · search · selected record · drafts · editing field where practical

## V2 (not V1)

History clock (last 5–10 places) — defer until Previous Screen is proven.

## Tests

Stack unit tests · Profile migration regression · destination wiring · Living Place leave restores origin
